<div id="content">
<h1 class="title">Notes</h1>
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Protestantism
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>16th C Protestant Reformation of the Catholic interpretation of Christianity advanced principles sympathetic to the scientific method, which had a disproportionate impact on the development of the sciences (See R.K. Merton and de Candolle's work)
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Absence of Inquisition</li>
<li>Protestant individualist ethos (seek truth yourself)</li>
<li>"the priest hood of all believers"</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Use of science for religions ends (e.g. Calvinist 'good works')
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>"To study the nature and course and use of all God's works is a duty imposed by God upon all sorts of men&#x2026;[it] would enlarge our hearts to God and our skil to usefulnesse to ourselves and others" &#x2013; John Cotton</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Britain first to allow different denominations to freely operate in the same country</li>
<li>Aligned cosmology and theology
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Renounce hierarchy of rule (levels of angels and delegation of duties) in favour of God's direct intervention and predetermined laws (e.g. Preston, and rise of absolute monarchs centred like the sun). More open to the plurality of worlds and an infinite universe (see Bruno and Leibniz)</li>
</ul></li>
</ul></li>
<li>Stuttered starts: Italy, Germany, Russia
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>1560s Academia Secretorum Naturae in Naples</li>
<li>1601 Accademia dei Lincei in Rome</li>
<li>1657 Academia del Cimento in Florence
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>members created the barometer, thermometers, measured the velocity of sound, demonstrated that insects do not spontaneously form</li>
</ul></li>
<li>1622 Societas Ereunetica in Rostock</li>
<li>1672 Collegium Curiosum sive Experimentale in Altdorf</li>
<li>1700 Berlin Academy
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Adopted many French savants (e.g. Maupertuis, Lamettrie, Voltaire, Lagrange)</li>
</ul></li>
<li>1724 St. Petersburg Academy
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Adopted many Swiss scientists (e.g. Nicholas Bernoulli, Leonard Euler)</li>
</ul></li>
</ul></li>
<li>Western Europe
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>French Salons
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>1620 Aix gathering (including Gassendi), Marin Mersenne's cell in Paris (corresponding with Descartes, Hobbes, Galileo, Fermat, Pascal&#x2026;)</li>
<li>1666 Paris Academy of Sciences
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Professional scientists paid by the king and given designated work</li>
<li>Shift to more literarry and philosophical concerns of science</li>
<li>Until the French Revolution, many provincial centres around France fruitfully contributed</li>
</ul></li>
<li>1644 British Philosophical College
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>1660/2 British Royal college for the promoting of physico-mathematical experimental learning', which became 'The Royal society for the Imprpovement of Natural Knowledge'</li>
</ul></li>
</ul></li>
</ul></li>
<li>British Rise
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>John Wilkins (1614-72) defended the Copernican system and hypothesised about other inhabited planets and the equality of Earth with them (1638's <i>Discovery of a New World</i> and 1640's <i>Discourse Concerning a New Planet</i>)
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Divine anti-instrumentalism &amp; parsimony</li>
<li>Nature never uses "any tedious difficult means to perform that which may as well be accomplished by shorter and easier means"</li>
</ul></li>
<li>He also promoted the use of science in craft and industry (beyond the navigation and commers of others)</li>
<li>Leader of 'Philosophical College' group including other notables like chemist Robert Black, and the 'Philosophical Society' at Oxford, which included Christopher Wren and Thomas Sydenham</li>
<li>1640s Almanac makers in Britain start to favor Tychonian and Copernican (over Ptolemaic) systems</li>
</ul></li>
<li>British Royal Society
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Baconian influence to attend to the crafts/industries and collection of information:
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Histories and descriptions of shipping, clothing Manufacturing, dye trade, chemical uses</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Aims to improve all natural and useful knowledge and "not meddling with Divinity, Metaphysics, Moralls, Politicks, Grammar, Rhetorick, or Logick" (Hooke)</li>
<li>Established 8 committees for specific pursuits (e.g. mechanical, agriculture, astronomy, trades histories)</li>
<li>1671 Isaac Newton (1642-1727) becomes a Fellow, and from 1703 onward, the president of the Society</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Isaac Newton
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Difficult childhood</li>
<li>1661 attends Cambridge
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>"Amicus Plato amicus Aristoteles magis amica veritas"</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Lucasian Professor of Mathematics by 1669</li>
<li>1665-1666 immense creative output (largely journals)</li>
<li>Around this time prepared <i>Philosophiae Naturalis Principia Mathematica (Mathematical Principles of Natural Philosophy)</i>, though not published until 1687</li>
<li>1672 voted a fellow of hte Royal Society</li>
<li>1689 elected Parliment</li>
<li>1699 Master of the Royal Mint</li>
<li>1703 Elected President of the Royal Society</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
</div>
